{{Infobox oil refinery | name = Hovensa | image = HOVENSA_refinery-06.jpg | caption = Hovensa refinery, [[St. Croix]], [[United States Virgin Islands]] | location_map = US Virgin Islands Saint Croix | location_map_text = Location of Hovensa Refinery in Saint Croix | coordinates = {{coord|17|42|16|N|64|45|19|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = [[United States Virgin Islands]] | province = [[St. Croix]] | city = [[Christiansted, United States Virgin Islands|Christiansted]] | operator = Hovensa LLC | owner = [[Hess Corporation]], [[Petroleos de Venezuela]] | founded = {{Start date|1966}} | closure = | capacity = | capacity_bbl/d = 500000 | capacity for toluene = 294000 tonnes per year in 2011 | employees = | ref units = | oil tank = | oil refining center = }} '''Hovensa''' (known also as '''St. Croix Refinery''') was a petroleum refinery located on the island of [[St. Croix]] in the [[United States Virgin Islands]]. The refinery was a joint venture between [[Hess Corporation]] and [[Petroleos de Venezuela]]. For most of its operating life as HOVENSA it supplied heating oil and gasoline to the U.S. Gulf Coast and the eastern seaboard with the crude mainly sourced from [[Venezuela]]. Previously it had sourced its crude feedstock from a number of other countries including [[Libya]]. At a capacity of about {{convert|500000|oilbbl/d}} as of 2010 it was in the top 10 largest refineries in the world.<ref name=downstream151008> {{cite news | publisher=Downstream Today | url= http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=13338 | title= Omar Shuts Down Hovensa | agency = [[Agence France-Presse|AFX News Limited]] | date=2008-10-15 | accessdate=2010-07-08}} </ref><ref name=downstream201008> {{cite news | publisher=Downstream Today | url= http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=13385 | title= Hovensa Refinery Reopens | agency = [[Agence France-Presse|AFX News Limited]] | date=2008-10-20 | accessdate=2010-07-08}} </ref><ref name=downstream300609> {{cite news | publisher=Downstream Today | url= http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=16943 | title= Hovensa Defers Capital Projects, Trims Workforce | first =Susan | last = Daker | agency = [[Dow Jones Newswires]] | date=2009-06-30 | accessdate=2010-07-08}} </ref>
Hess Oil Virgin Islands Corporation started refinery construction in January 1966 having purchased the property from [[Annie de Chabert]] and, in October of the same year, the refinery started operating.<ref name=herald> {{cite news | url= http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2002/vol6n16/CBInstabVenez-en.html | title= Instability In Venezuela Being Watched Closely | first = John | last = Collins | newspaper = Puerto Rico Herald | date=2002-04-18 | accessdate=2011-06-27}} </ref> In 1974, the capacity of refinery was expanded up to its peak at {{convert|650000|oilbbl/d}}. Hovensa LLC, which took over the refinery operatorship, was established in 1998.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}
In January 2011, Hovensa paid a $5.3&nbsp;million penalty for Clean Air Act violations.<ref name=emcs> {{cite press release |url = http://employee-medical-credentialing.com/news_2011/2nd_largest_refinery_to_pay_5_3_million_penalty_for_clean_air_act_violations.html |title = 2ND Largest Refinery To Pay $5.3 Million Penalty For Clean Air Act Violations |publisher = Employee Medical Credentialing Services |date = 2011-01-27 |accessdate = 2012-01-20 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120317163100/http://employee-medical-credentialing.com/news_2011/2nd_largest_refinery_to_pay_5_3_million_penalty_for_clean_air_act_violations.html |archivedate = 2012-03-17 |df = }} </ref> On January 18, 2012 the company announced that it would close the refinery by mid-February 2012. The company sought to close the refinery and have the property serve as only a storage terminal.<ref name=ap180112> {{cite news | url= http://www.toledoblade.com/Energy/2012/01/18/Hovensa-LLC-to-shut-Virgin-Islands-oil-refinery.html | title= Hovensa LLC to shut Virgin Islands oil refinery | first = Jason | last = Bronis | agency = [[Associated Press]] | work = Toledo Blade | date=2012-01-18 | accessdate=2012-01-20}} </ref>
In the summer of 2018, a Boston-based private equity firm announced plans to acquire the facility and resume refinery operations by 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-refinery-virginislands/st-croix-oil-refinery-gets-1-4-billion-investment-plans-to-restart-idUSKBN1JS1TZ|title=St. Croix oil refinery gets $1.4 billion investment, plans to restart|last=Eaton|first=Collin|date=July 2, 2018|work=Reuters.com|access-date=2018-09-06|language=en-US}}</ref>
