[[File:Marmok-a-5-buoy.jpg|thumb]]
'''MARMOK-A-5''' is an offshore electrical power generator that uses wave energy to create electricity. This device is a spar buoy installed in the maritime testing site Bimep, in the Bay of Biscay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tidalenergytoday.com/2016/10/13/wave-energy-device-hits-bimep-waters/|title=Wave energy device hits Bimep waters|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="Phys">{{cite web|title=Wave energy device successfully deployed at BiMEP site|url=https://phys.org/news/2016-11-energy-device-successfully-deployed-bimep.html|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref><ref name="Opera">{{cite web|title=OCEANTEC deployed at BiMEP its first wave energy converter - OPERA H2020|url=http://opera-h2020.eu/?p=657|website=OPERA H2020|accessdate=1 January 2018|date=13 October 2016}}</ref> It is the first grid connected maritime generator in Spain, and one of the first in the word.
Developed by the Basque company Oceantec Energias Marinas inside the European project OPERA, it is delivering electrical energy to the grid since December 2016. The buoy is located in the ocean, 4Km from the coastline and is connected to the sea with a submarine electrical cable. With a nominal power of 30kW, the principal aim of the MARMOK-A-5 device is obtaining results in the way of designing a new generation cost effective high power marine energy generator.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tecnalia.com/es/energia-medioambiente/noticias/oceantec-instala-en-bimep-su-primer-dispositivo-para-el-aprovechamiento-de-la-energia-de-las-olas.htm |date=2016-10-13 |title=Oceantec instala en BiMEP su primer dispositivo para el aprovechamiento de la energía de las olas}} </ref>
== Principle == The operation principle of MARMOK-A-5 is a point absorber OWC ([[Oscillating Water Column]]). The device is 5m in diameter and a length of 42m,<ref name="Hydroworld">{{cite web|title=Oceantec wave energy device online in Spain|url=http://www.hydroworld.com/articles/2016/11/oceantec-marmok-a-5-commissioned-at-bimep-in-spain.html|website=Hydroworld|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> 6m above the water. It has a weight of more than 80 tons. The bouy is floating in a 90m depth and is tied to the sea bed with a mooring system based on anchors. This wave energy converter has demonstrated its robustness surviving difficult environmental conditions with waves as big as 12m.
